I don't agree with this. The punishment should fit the crime.
The threshold for Byzantine behavior for training is lower than most fault-tolerant systems (BFT, Bitcoin, etc.).
So if a miner's behavior in one window can damage an entire run, or it takes 200 windows to recover from it, then the punishment should scale accordingly.

While I empathize with anyone not making emissions right now, we believe that the current incentive mechanism is helping accelerate the subnet towards its goals: fast convergence and decentralized training.

As subnet designers, our only job is to create an incentive mechanism that pushes miners to continually decrease the loss.

If we look through that lens, we are doing pretty well.

The aim is not "everyone earns," it's that the people who produce the best earn the most, as they accelerate the subnet to our goals.

However, there is room for improvement, as the current landscape locks in early winners, and there is a weird type of UID pressure.

There are advantages to being evaluated earlier. As long as we have this, there will always be an element of chance.

We will continue to iterate on it, as we do really want as much of the community to be involved.

I just can't see how I can design an incentive landscape with "let's make sure many miners earn."

It has to be a second order effect if that happens.

I am not saying that it's not a good thing, but it's not a core objective.

The day we start to design like that , gamma becomes "a slow rug" , as I can't see how we succeed. 

So in a way , its also whats best for gamma holders
